titlestmt.titleproper: A Guide to the Joshua Lederberg personal papers, Subject File FA1087

did.unittitle: Joshua Lederberg personal papers, Subject File

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Minimal processing. Many records remain in original file folders.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Information regarding the Rockefeller Archive Center's preferred elements and forms of citation can be found at http://www.rockarch.org/research/citations.php

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection comprises Lederberg's personal subect files primarily documenting his interests and activities outside that of Rockefeller University including but not limited to: Cetus Corporation, Recombinant DNA, the Human Frontier Science Program, National Science Foundation (NSF), National Cancer Institute (NCI), National Resources Defense Council, Annual Reviews, Inc., Institute for Scientific Information (ISI), National Academy of Science (NAS), and his work with NASA, particularly the Viking Mission to Mars. The collection also includes select subject files from Rockefeller University as well as his work at Stanford University.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Joshua Lederberg was most prominantly known for his work in the fields of molecular biology, artificial intellegence, exobiology, human rights advocacy, as well as his science and public policy advisory to nine U.S. Presidents, and his prominent role with the National Aeuronautics Space Administration (NASA) missions to Mars.

For his work with genetic transfer among bacteria Lederberg shared the 1958 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine with Edward Tatum and George Beadle. For his lifetime of achievement Lederberg was also recognized with the 1989 National Medal of Science and the 2006 Presidential Medal of Freedom.
For a detailed biography of Joshua Lederberg, please see the Rockefeller University "Awards and Honors" website.
